  <EntryCount>100</EntryCount>
  <Entries>
    <Entry>
      <ID>1</ID>
      <DefaultText>The philethis stands before you, hidden inside the bulk of its armor-cloth robes, unmoving and unmoved by your presence. 

Exactly who, or what, the thing is - man or machine, mutant or monster - is impossible to discern. Its glass face reveals nothing but your reflection; its mechanical voice reveals nothing at all.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>2</ID>
      <DefaultText>[Ask it about Zenia's sphere.]</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>3</ID>
      <DefaultText>Leave it alone.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>4</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Death is the point where the lines intersect."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>6</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Exquisite?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>7</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You are exquisite as well."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>8</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Thank you for the compliment."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>10</ID>
      <DefaultText>"No," the thing answers. "It is not."

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>11</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>12</ID>
      <DefaultText>Philethis are said to have vast knowledge of the mysteries of the Ninth World and the numenera of ages past, but prying those secrets loose can be a fool's errand.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>13</ID>
      <DefaultText>A sound like the grinding of drit-filled gears is the thing's only response.

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>14</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>15</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>16</ID>
      <DefaultText>"The glass does not create, though it bends."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>17</ID>
      <DefaultText>The philethis are said to have vast knowledge of the mysteries of the Ninth World and the numenera of ages past, but prying those secrets loose can be a fool's errand.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>18</ID>
      <DefaultText>Philethis are said to have vast knowledge of the mysteries of the Ninth World and the numenera of ages past, but prying those secrets loose can be a fool's errand.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>28</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>29</ID>
      <DefaultText>For a moment that stretches uncomfortably, you feel the cold scrutiny of the philethis upon you. At last, it speaks again. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>30</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You burn, but there is no light."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>35</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You reckon, but the figures are incommensurable."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>36</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You ask, but the world rebukes."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>37</ID>
      <DefaultText>"The sun cannot warm the vastness between the worlds."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>38</ID>
      <DefaultText>"It is the nature of flags to fade."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>39</ID>
      <DefaultText>
You sense there is something the Philethis wants from you.  Perhaps you can gain something in the process.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>41</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>44</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Do you know anything about Zenia's sphere? She wants to know what she's seeing in it and why."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>45</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Please, tell me about yourself."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>46</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Do you know anything about the Sorrow?  About the resonance chamber built by the Changing God?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>47</ID>
      <DefaultText>[Tidal Surge] Force it to tell you about itself.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>48</ID>
      <DefaultText>Leave it alone.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>49</ID>
      <DefaultText>As you step away, the philethis swivels to keep its glass face trained upon you.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>50</ID>
      <DefaultText>The philethis regards you silently, implacably, still scrutinizing, still seeking.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>51</ID>
      <DefaultText>  All the same, you have the sense that it still wants something from you.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>63</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Tell me about yourself."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>64</ID>
      <DefaultText>For a moment, the philethis's face darkens. Then, without inflection, it answers: "The cursed qui hungers, and it feeds, but it is denied satiation."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>67</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>68</ID>
      <DefaultText>"The avatrol whistles while it runs, a fearful sound. Perhaps even for the avatrol."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>69</ID>
      <DefaultText>They whistle because of the gaping holes in their skulls. Whether the philethis intends an insult, a joke, or something else is entirely unclear.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>70</ID>
      <DefaultText>"No."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>71</ID>
      <DefaultText>Silence lingers long, until at last the philethis speaks: "Others watch, also. Others change, also. They seek an undoing."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>73</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>74</ID>
      <DefaultText>"What do you want from me?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>75</ID>
      <DefaultText>{SCRIPT: This option should not be available if the philethis has nothing more to ask you.}  "What more do you want from me?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>80</ID>
      <DefaultText>When the philethis at last answers, its mechanical voice seems to creak. "You did not accept [THING YOU DECLINED]. When you are served the bitter root, will you eat?"

{ADAM/GEORGE: Same drill as node 107, except with instances where the player declined something, a reward or an offer. SCRIPT: This will probably require a slight bit more variation in the text for the various possibilities.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>81</ID>
      <DefaultText>A surge of tidal energy pours from you into the philethis. The creature's bulky armor-cloth robes flap and flutter as if caught in a windstorm, and its glass face scintillates wildly, refracting and reflecting the forces brought to bear upon it. 

A shrill keening, like a teapot brought to boil, blasts through your mind, as a fracture spreads across the philethis's impregnable mask.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>82</ID>
      <DefaultText>Then, you *feel* it: a hole inside of you, like something torn away, a truth, an unknown answer to an unknown question, a name, a self. You crumple with the weakness of hollow things and imagine armoring yourself in a false enigma, obscuring your shame through obscurity, and scrounging through the world's drit for a lone lost grain.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>83</ID>
      <DefaultText>As you tremble, the Philetis's face goes black, and it speaks a short, uninflected phrase: "One sees himself in the glass, though it bends."

Then, the feeling is gone, and so too is the philethis.

{SCRIPT: The philethis disappears. It can reappear in later areas, but will disappear at your approach.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>85</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I've seen you before, haven't I?"

{SCRIPT: Assuming you spoke (or attempted to speak to) to the philethis in a prior area.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>86</ID>
      <DefaultText>"The hall was dark, and the plasmar gleamed. Together, we posed questions."

That seems the only answer it intends to give.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>90</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You've been following me?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>91</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Why are you so interested in my choices?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>92</ID>
      <DefaultText>"What do these questions mean?  What do you *want*?"

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>93</ID>
      <DefaultText>In its slow rumble, the philethis replies, "They are not yours."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>94</ID>
      <DefaultText>"In memory, cause follows effect. In rain, the colors run." A long rumble suggests that the philethis has more to say, but nothing emerges.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>95</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Yes." The single, flat word lingers in the air, until the philethis adds, "What *is* the answer?"

Perhaps the thing wants you to answer your own question.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>96</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You want to know if I am drawing the Sorrow to this place."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>97</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You want to understand why I have done what I have done."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>98</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You want to confound me."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>99</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You don't know what you want."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>101</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I don't know."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>102</ID>
      <DefaultText>The philethis accepts your answer silently, giving no clue as to what pases within its impervious robes, behind its impenetrable mask.

At last, when it seems no response will come, a single word, no longer quite so flat, escapes: "Yes..."

Then all is silent once more.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>103</ID>
      <DefaultText>The philethis accepts your answer silently, giving no clue as to what pases within its impervious robes, behind its impenetrable mask.

At last, when it seems no response will come, the thing speaks: "The glass reflects."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>104</ID>
      <DefaultText>As if in confirmation, the philethis accepts your answer silently, giving no clue as to what pass with its impervious robes, behind its impenetrable mask.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>105</ID>
      <DefaultText>The philethis accepts your answer silently, giving no clue as to what pases within its impervious robes, behind its impenetrable mask. 

At last, the thing replies: "The world has died a hundred deaths, and there is pebble in your left shoe."

You shake the pebble loose, have gotten something, at least, from the conversation.

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>106</ID>
      <DefaultText>The philethis accepts your answer silently, giving no clue as to what pases within its impervious robes, behind its impenetrable mask. 

At last, the thing replies: "The nose does not smell with words."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>107</ID>
      <DefaultText>The philethis ponders silently, until at last it asks, "When you fought [WHATEVER TUSSLE], why did you not step first with your left foot?"


{ADAM/GEORGE: We should probably do three or four different possible tussles here to reduce the risk of the player not having done one. Then it can just select the first one that took place. There are no specifics entailed in the question. SCRIPT: There will be some slight variations of this first question, but it will only ask about a tussle once before going on to the next question. I guess this should be a bank event perhaps?}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>108</ID>
      <DefaultText>Its words so rushed they almost jumble together, the philethis asks, "When you took the [item], which way did your *shadow* fall?"






{ADAM/GEORGE: Same drill as nodes 80, 107, with collecting loot. SCRIPT: Same drill.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>109</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You want to know *everything.*"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>110</ID>
      <DefaultText>The philethis accepts your answer silently, giving no clue as to what pases within its impervious robes, behind its impenetrable mask.

At last, the thing replies: "All is as one. But one is not as the rest."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>111</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Yes."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>112</ID>
      <DefaultText>"No."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>116</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I had no reason."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>117</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Balance, probably."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>118</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I assume it placed me in a better position."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>119</ID>
      <DefaultText>The philethis accepts your answer in silence, giving no sign of satisfaction, frustration, or curiosity.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>120</ID>
      <DefaultText>Again, the philethis shows no response to your answer.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>121</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I don't know."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>123</ID>
      <DefaultText>(Guess) "Before me."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>124</ID>
      <DefaultText>(Guess) "Behind me."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>125</ID>
      <DefaultText>(Guess) "Beside me."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>126</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I have no idea."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>127</ID>
      <DefaultText>A long rumble echoes from inside the philethis's robes, changing at last to words: "In the village of Thome, it is written, 'The eremite Alageiser descended deep into the darkness, for he could not bear to see his shadow.'"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>133</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Exquisite."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>135</ID>
      <DefaultText>""No."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>138</ID>
      <DefaultText>You know little of Navarene beyond the proverbial wealth of its merchants, but, regardless, the philethis comes from someplace far more distant than the Steadfast.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>140</ID>
      <DefaultText>The philethis's face whirls with vortices of energy, and a great groaning of gears resounds from its hidden form. This struggle complete, its face goes blank once more, and it speaks. 

"In Navarene, a merchant has locked himself in his vault, surrounded by silks and cyphers and shins, without a drop to drink. He will know need and regret before the end."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>143</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>146</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Exquisite," the philethis grates, in greeting perhaps, or perhaps lost in its own inscrutable thoughts.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>157</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>158</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>159</ID>
      <DefaultText>The Philethis's implacable glass gaze seems to bore through your skin and see more than others do, and you sense there is something it wants from you.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>160</ID>
      <DefaultText>
You sense there is something more the Philethis wants from you.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>165</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>166</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You ask, but the world rebukes."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>167</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You burn, but there is no light."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>168</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You reckon, but the figures are incommensurable."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>169</ID>
      <DefaultText>"The sun cannot warm the vastness between the worlds."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>170</ID>
      <DefaultText>"It is the nature of flags to fade."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>172</ID>
      <DefaultText>The philethis's implacable glass gaze bores through your skin and sees more than others do - and it seems to be seeking something from you.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>173</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
